1. Concept

An array is a collection of elements stored in contiguous memory locations.
Each element is accessed using an index.

Indexing usually starts from 0.

Example:
Array: [10, 20, 30, 40]
Index:  0   1   2   3

So:
arr[0] = 10
arr[1] = 20
arr[2] = 30
arr[3] = 40

Arrays store multiple values in a single variable.

2.Why Arrays Are Used

Arrays help to:
• Store many values together
• Access elements using index
• Process data efficiently using loops

Example use cases:

Storing marks of students
List of prices
Tracking scores

3. Visual Explanation

Example:

arr = [5, 8, 2, 7]

Memory representation:

Index →   0    1    2    3
        ---------------------
Array → | 5 | 8 | 2 | 7 |
        ---------------------

Each box stores a value.

4.Common Patterns in Array Problems

When solving interview problems, arrays often follow these patterns.

1. Traversal

Visit each element.

Example:

Find maximum element
Find minimum element
Sum of array
2. Two Pointer Technique

Used when working with:
• sorted arrays
• pairs
• reversing arrays

Example problems:
Two Sum
Reverse Array
Remove Duplicates

3. Sliding Window

Used when dealing with:
subarrays
maximum/minimum sums
fixed window sizes

Example:
Maximum sum subarray
Longest substring

4. Prefix Sum

Used when repeatedly calculating range sums.

Example:
Sum from index L to R
Instead of recalculating each time, we precompute cumulative sums.

Example:

Array: [1,2,3,4]

Prefix Sum:
[1,3,6,10]

